# Phase 2 — Full Network Rollout

Status: **In Progress**

Phase 1 validated Pi-hole on 2 personal devices by manually changing each
device's DNS settings. That doesn't scale and misses devices that can't be
easily configured — smart TVs, IoT sensors, game consoles, and guest
devices. Phase 2 moves DNS resolution to the router's DHCP server so every
device on the network is covered automatically, with zero per-device setup.

---

## Why Router DHCP Instead of Per-Device

| Approach | Coverage | Effort Per New Device |
|---|---|---|
| Per-device DNS (Phase 1) | Only configured devices | Manual, every time |
| **Router DHCP DNS (Phase 2)** | Every device automatically | Zero — inherited from DHCP |
| Pi-hole's own DHCP server | Every device automatically | Zero, but requires disabling router's DHCP |

This lab uses **router DHCP DNS override** — non-destructive, reversible in
one click, and doesn't require disabling the router's own DHCP server.

---

## Step 1 — Confirm Pi-hole Has a Static IP

Before touching the router, Pi-hole's IP must never change. If it shifts
after a reboot, every device on the network loses DNS simultaneously.

```bash
ip a show eth0
cat /etc/netplan/*.yaml
```

Either set a static IP on the Ubuntu host directly, or create a DHCP
reservation on the router tying Pi-hole's MAC address to its current IP
permanently. Skipping this is the most common cause of "the whole network
lost internet" after a Pi-hole DHCP rollout.

---

## Step 2 — Find the DHCP DNS Setting on Your Router

| Router Brand | Typical Menu Path |
|---|---|
| Asus | LAN → DHCP Server → DNS Server 1 |
| Netgear | Advanced → Setup → LAN Setup → Use This DNS Server |
| TP-Link | Advanced → Network → DHCP Server → Primary DNS |
| Ubiquiti / UniFi | Settings → Networks → (LAN) → DHCP Name Server |
| ISP-provided router | Varies — look for "DHCP" or "LAN Setup"; some ISP routers restrict this |

---

## Step 3 — Set Primary DNS to Pi-hole, Secondary as Fallback

```
Primary DNS Server   = <your Pi-hole static IP>
Secondary DNS Server = 1.1.1.1   # fallback ONLY if Pi-hole is down
```

> **Nuance:** some devices treat secondary DNS as a load-balanced
> alternative rather than a strict fallback — meaning some queries may
> bypass Pi-hole entirely. For maximum blocking coverage, some builders set
> secondary DNS to Pi-hole's own IP again, accepting that DNS fails
> completely if Pi-hole goes down. This lab prioritises uptime over maximum
> blocking by using 1.1.1.1 as secondary — document whichever tradeoff you
> choose.

