## IoT, Guest Network & Devices That Resist DNS Changes

Some devices ignore DHCP-provided DNS and hardcode their own (common on
smart speakers, some streaming sticks, and IoT sensors shipped with Google
or Cloudflare DNS baked in for reliability).

**Detecting these devices:**

```bash
sudo tcpdump -i eth0 'udp port 53 and dst host 8.8.8.8'
```

Any device shown here is bypassing Pi-hole entirely. Fixing this typically
requires a router-level DNS redirect (intercepting all outbound port 53
traffic regardless of destination) — more invasive and router-dependent,
worth pursuing only if specific devices are confirmed to be bypassing
Pi-hole.

**Guest network decision:**

| Network | Recommendation | Reasoning |
|---|---|---|
| Main LAN | Route through Pi-hole | Trusted devices, full benefit of blocking/visibility |
| Guest network | Keep on default/ISP DNS | Network segmentation — don't expose internal infrastructure to untrusted guest devices |
| IoT VLAN (if configured) | Route through Pi-hole | IoT devices benefit most from blocking telemetry/tracking |

