## Apps, Streaming Services & YouTube — What Actually Works

Testing ad blocking on streaming apps and YouTube specifically revealed an
important structural limitation worth documenting honestly rather than
overselling.

| Platform | DNS Blocking Result | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Roku (ads/telemetry) | Works well | Ad servers separate from content delivery |
| Samsung Smart TV (ads/telemetry) | Works well | Ad/tracking domains isolated from app function |
| Mobile apps (general ads) | Works well | Most ad SDKs use dedicated ad-serving domains |
| Amazon Prime Video | Partial | Some ad domains separate, some bundled with content |
| Hulu / Paramount+ | Inconsistent | Ad infrastructure changes frequently |
| **YouTube** | **Does not work reliably** | Video and ads both stream from `googlevideo.com` — same domain |
| **Netflix** | **Does not work** | No DNS-level ad domains exist; ads are server-side inserted |

YouTube ad-blocking regex lists circulating online either fail to block
ads at all or block so aggressively that videos refuse to play. Google
deliberately rotates these subdomains to defeat this kind of filtering —
this was not added to this lab's blocklists.

For YouTube specifically, device-level tools are what actually work:
ReVanced (Android, patches the app directly), SmartTube (Android TV
alternative client), or uBlock Origin (desktop browser). These operate
outside DNS entirely and are a deliberate complement to this lab, not a
replacement for it.

**Smart TV telemetry blocklist used in this lab** (safe — does not touch
content-serving domains):

```bash
docker exec -it pihole bash

pihole-FTL sqlite3 /etc/pihole/gravity.db \
  "INSERT INTO adlist (address, enabled, comment) VALUES \
  ('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/AnimAlmamun/blocklist/master/SmartTV-AGH.txt', 1, 'SmartTV-Telemetry');"

pihole -g
```

